Below is a complete, clean, copy-paste-ready assessment pack that you can run in your environment to fully analyze:

âœ” The materialized view definition
âœ” Its refresh method and history
âœ” Its dependencies
âœ” Whether it is VALID or NEEDS_COMPILE
âœ” Whether any jobs are refreshing it
âœ” Whether FAST refresh is even possible
âœ” Whether the source view changed
âœ” Whether objects in the dependency chain are INVALID

This gives you everything DBAs normally collect before troubleshooting MV performance.

âœ… SECTION 1 â€” Check materialized view definition (core metadata)

SELECT mview_name,
       owner,
       container_name,
       container_id,
       staleness,
       build_mode,
       refresh_mode,
       refresh_method,
       last_refresh_type,
       last_refresh_date,
       compile_state,
       interval
FROM dba_mviews
WHERE owner = 'LC_SCMT'
  AND mview_name = 'VW_FCSMT_GFIU_NEW_M';

Interpretation:
STALENESS = NEEDS_COMPILE â†’ MV must be compiled or recreated
REFRESH_METHOD = COMPLETE or FAST
REFRESH_MODE = ON DEMAND or ON COMMIT
INTERVAL NOT NULL â†’ MV refresh scheduled at object level

âœ… SECTION 2 â€” Retrieve the actual MV DDL (definition)

SELECT DBMS_METADATA.GET_DDL('MATERIALIZED_VIEW',
                             'VW_FCSMT_GFIU_NEW_M',
                             'LC_SCMT')
FROM DUAL;

This shows:
The SELECT used to populate the MV
All refresh options
Storage, logging, tablespace, etc.
If this returns (CLOB), click the CLOB to view it.

âœ… SECTION 3 â€” Check MV refresh history (scheduler logs)

SELECT job_name,
       status,
       actual_start_date,
       run_duration,
       error#,
       additional_info
FROM dba_scheduler_job_run_details
WHERE job_name LIKE '%GFIU%'
ORDER BY actual_start_date DESC;

This tells you:
When refreshes fail
Why (ORA error)
Runtime duration

âœ… SECTION 4 â€” Check if there is a scheduler job refreshing it

SELECT job_name,
       enabled,
       state,
       last_start_date,
       next_run_date,
       schedule_name,
       job_action
FROM dba_scheduler_jobs
WHERE UPPER(job_action) LIKE '%GFIU%'
   OR job_name LIKE '%GFIU%';

âœ… SECTION 5 â€” Check if DBMS_JOB (legacy job) refreshes it

SELECT job, what, last_date, next_date, interval, failures
FROM dba_jobs
WHERE WHAT LIKE '%GFIU%'
   OR WHAT LIKE '%VW_FCSMT_GFIU_NEW_M%';

âœ… SECTION 6 â€” Check MV dependencies (critical)

SELECT *
FROM dba_dependencies
WHERE name = 'VW_FCSMT_GFIU_NEW_M'
  AND owner = 'LC_SCMT'
ORDER BY referenced_owner, referenced_name;

You will see:
Base view (VW_FCSMT_GFIU_NEW_FF)
Any tables it uses
Any other objects (views, synonyms)

âœ… SECTION 7 â€” Check VALID/INVALID status of dependent objects

SELECT owner, object_name, object_type, status
FROM dba_objects
WHERE owner = 'LC_SCMT'
  AND object_name IN (
        'VW_FCSMT_GFIU_NEW_M',
        'VW_FCSMT_GFIU_NEW_FF'
      );

If either object is INVALID â†’ refresh will fail.

âœ… SECTION 8 â€” Check if FAST refresh is even possible

SELECT log_owner, master, log_table
FROM dba_mview_logs
WHERE master IN (
  SELECT referenced_name
  FROM dba_dependencies
  WHERE name = 'VW_FCSMT_GFIU_NEW_FF'
    AND owner = 'LC_SCMT'
);

If this returns zero rows, FAST refresh is impossible.

âœ… SECTION 9 â€” Check row count & size of MV

SELECT COUNT(*) AS rows_in_mv
FROM LC_SCMT.VW_FCSMT_GFIU_NEW_M;

For segment size:

SELECT segment_name, bytes/1024/1024 MB
FROM dba_segments
WHERE segment_name = 'VW_FCSMT_GFIU_NEW_M'
  AND owner = 'LC_SCMT';


âœ… SECTION 10 â€” Check column list of MV source view (to detect breaking changes)

SELECT column_id, column_name, data_type
FROM dba_tab_columns
WHERE owner = 'LC_SCMT'
  AND table_name = 'VW_FCSMT_GFIU_NEW_FF'
ORDER BY column_id;

If column list changed after 08/08/2025 â†’ MV must be recreated.

